2026-03-02 | Trapping Rain Water

	Question
Given arr[],
return how much rainwater can be trapped.

	Approach 1 (Classic Idea)
1.	Water above index i is determined by:
		min(max height to left, max height to right) − arr[i]
2.	Brute force would be O(n²).
3.	Better approach:
		Precompute leftMax[] and rightMax[].
4.	Then sum up water at each index.

	Time Complexity: O(n)
	Space Complexity: O(n)

	Better Optimized Approach (Two Pointers)

	Optimized Approach (O(1) space)
1.	Use two pointers:
		left = 0
		right = n−1
2.	Maintain:
		leftMax
		rightMax
3.	While left < right:
		If arr[left] < arr[right]:
			If arr[left] ≥ leftMax:
				update leftMax
			Else:
				add leftMax − arr[left] to answer
			left++
		Else:
			If arr[right] ≥ rightMax:
				update rightMax
			Else:
				add rightMax − arr[right] to answer
			right--
4.	Time Complexity:
		O(n)
5.	Space Complexity:
		O(1)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int trap(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        if (n <= 2) return 0;

        int left = 0, right = n - 1;
        int leftMax = 0, rightMax = 0;
        int water = 0;

        while (left < right) {
            if (arr[left] < arr[right]) {
                if (arr[left] >= leftMax)
                    leftMax = arr[left];
                else
                    water += leftMax - arr[left];
                left++;
            } else {
                if (arr[right] >= rightMax)
                    rightMax = arr[right];
                else
                    water += rightMax - arr[right];
                right--;
            }
        }

        return water;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Water trapped at each position depends on
the smaller of the maximum heights
on both sides.
Two-pointer technique computes this efficiently
in linear time with constant space.
